â€¢ Encapsulation in Java
âž£ Wrapping (binding) data (variables) and methods (functions) into a single unit, i.e., a class
âž£ Restricting direct access to data by using access modifiers and exposing controlled access through methods

â€¢ In simple terms:
âž£ Encapsulation = Data Hiding + Controlled Access

â€¢ How Encapsulation Is Achieved in Java
âƒ Encapsulation is implemented using:
âƒ Private data members
âƒ Public getter and setter methods
âƒ Access modifiers

â€¢ Steps:
â–¸ Declare variables as private
â–¸ Provide public methods to access/update them

â€¢ Advantages of Encapsulation 
1. Data Security
âž¥ Prevents unauthorized access
âž¥ Protects sensitive data (passwords, balances)

2. Controlled Access
âž¥ Validation logic can be added
âž¥ Only valid data enters the system

3. Improved Maintainability
âž¥ Internal implementation can change without affecting other classes
âž¥ Reduces impact of changes

4. Flexibility
âž¥ Read-only or write-only access possible
Example:
â Only get() â†’ read-only
â Only set() â†’ write-only

5. Better Modularity
âž¥ Each class manages its own data
âž¥ Cleaner architecture
